<p>You‚Äôre asking an expert to build something for you, whether it‚Äôs a new website, a landing page, e-commerce, whatever. A crucial information that will help them working their magic out is knowing who you‚Äôre targeting, your prospects. This way an expert can evaluate several factors (design, technology, etc.) that pertain to specific users and provide you with the best solution accordingly.</p>
<ol>
  <li>Design consideration and preferred aesthetic</li>
</ol>

<p>When it comes to qualitative and aesthetic considerations writing down all preferred elements isn‚Äôt the most suitable way to share that kind of information, while showing them is a better way. When writing your brief, add resources to leave misunderstandings out the door: try pairing any element of design you‚Äôd want with a description or comment. You can pick examples from websites, books, sketches, and anything you shows what you‚Äôre looking for. While the project is running, lead the expert with your feedback.</p>
<ol>
  <li>Success criteria</li>
</ol>

<p>One element that often get left out from a project brief is how you will measure the success of the project itself in an objective way: the KPIs. What are the Key Performance Indicators? They‚Äôre measurable metrics by which a project can be judged as a success (or not) in accordance with the client‚Äôs primary goal. Some examples of KPIs for web projects can be:</p>

